Text.Value: Not... mad, no. Take Sarevok, for example. For as much carnage as he caused, there was always a cold calculation to it.
The gods can grant power or strip it away - but so long as your will remains, you have the only weapon you need.
How did you end up joining?
I'm sorry. I hope I didn't bring up any bad memories.
And when we were married - on an upturned cart in the rainy Dalelands - he stammered so much, I've never been sure if our vows actually counted.

EditorData.NodeContext: General amused / fond rememberance

Text.Value: But happiness is not beyond a Bhaalspawn. It simply comes at a higher cost - constant vigilance.
But if you have questions - you've earned whatever answers I can give.
Tell me something about him no one else knows.
It was Bhaalspawn who threatened the Coast, and Bhaalspawn who saved it. It is possible to go on a live a life outside your father's shadow.
What need, when it seems so intent on repeating itself?

EditorData.NodeContext: Gently fobbing us off with a joke - she'll get into her past with us another time

Text.Value: I felt the way they think. Saw the world as they do. Foul, unnatural creatures, who find the foulness in us and twist it to their will.

EditorData.NodeContext: Recalling her time as an illithid thrall with utter distaste - to be robbed of free will is disgusting

Text.Value: You've already bested your father. I would advise against fighting the battle over again in your mind.
You were telling me about the Harpers.
They raised me in the wild. But when it became clear I was perhaps not suited to a life of idle reflection, I was sent to the Harpers. To do.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dry, amused at herself - she loves being a druid and living in nature, but always wanted to be active

Text.Value: Oh. Good. Then I am under no obligation to be wise.

EditorData.NodeContext: Pause for thought - content

Text.Value: Tell me what you know about Orin.
I learned young what fear and hunger make desperate people do. I learned to do some of it myself, even, until a roving circle of hedge-druids found me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Remembering bad years of her youth, but evenly, not great pathos or lingering trauma. She wound up luckier than most in her view.

Text.Value: It was Bhaal alone we faced in our time - and bad as that was, he had no elder brain for a lapdog then.
But, I suppose you have earned better than glibness from me. It was a gift from my husband. Khalid.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrugging, sighing - discarding humour to actually answer our question [Kal-eed]

Text.Value: Then greetings, saer tadpole. I was wondering where all the questions suddenly sprang from.

EditorData.NodeContext: Mock formality, bow.

Text.Value: I've passed enough years that counting them is a waste of what remains.

EditorData.NodeContext: Obfuscating her age as if coy - but bluntly confirming it in the next line.

Text.Value: And if it wriggles free, you'll find it still has teeth.
It sounds like you and the Harpers have a complicated history.
We learned to take them as a marker of pride. Even gods can be resisted.
Nothing that wasn't already there, fear not. But I've lived many lifetimes since Khalid died.

EditorData.NodeContext: Cocked eyebrow, amused - we haven't upset her

Text.Value: He craved power, and his bloodline was just another path to achieve it. I saw that same bloodline turned to better ends than Bhaal ever intended for it.
I will not bore you with a long tale. The short: I was born to a high family in Tethyr. I remember little, except that when my family fell, they fell far. And fast.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrug. She has a sob story like everyone, but isn't interested in indulging it

Text.Value: Did your friend ever tell you of the dreams Bhaal sent them?
No. They most certainly are not.

EditorData.NodeContext: Very nostalgic, former Jaheira romancers should feel a little heartbroken, but she shouldn't entirely imply it was her.

Text.Value: He had compassion. When you live a Harper's life, see all that a Harper sees, that is by far the harder thing to hold on to.

EditorData.NodeContext: Courage is overrated - any idiot can be brave

Text.Value: It is easy to get tired of the intrigue. The high causes shrouded in secrecy. I thought I might find another way to be of use to the world.
Oh, I'm sure time and an ageing mind have smoothed out a few of his flaws. But he was a good man.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrug - nostalgia tends to do that

Text.Value: I believe you. You remind me of another I knew, marked by forces beyond their control.

EditorData.NodeContext: Stated plainly.

Text.Value: Tell me about him.
In all my years fighting for the Harpers, I am still never certain what 'the greater good' means. I've learned to be content with: 'well, that was not so bad as it might have been'.
Which is my sage way of saying - I am in no danger of forgetting how my husband died. But I choose to remember how he lived.

EditorData.NodeContext: Amused at her own trite poeticalness in the line before, as Jaheira always must be. Grand phrases or no, it is what it is.

Text.Value: *The quiet, unassuming shadow to Jaheira's strength, Khalid was another warrior who helped end the Bhaalspawn Crisis. Shortly after, he was murdered by the mad mage Jon Irenicus.*
Ask about Khalid.
I did. Though I don't often speak of it - so many seem to think they know the whole story already, I find it a pity to correct them.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrugging - a little guarded about getting into stories of the old days

Text.Value: You fought in the Temple of Bhaal before. Would you be able to find it again?
Turn to other matters.
If I tried to spare Geraldus the same headaches, well - now you know why. And if he is half the Harper I suspect, it won't make a damned bit of difference.
You travelled with a child of Bhaal in times past, did you not?
Then you are wise.
The songs make much of Khalid's meekness. The quiet little Harper who had to keep a tight hold on his courage. But he had it when it counted. And, more than that:
But a bard can tell you all the rest. As for all the things they cannot... well. I shall just have to keep those for myself.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dry smile - that's all we're getting out of her.

Text.Value: Help won't come from the history books, or from any old tales I can spin you. This is your story to write.

EditorData.NodeContext: Style of "hate to break it to you, kid"

Text.Value: Please. You're only one of those things.
Yes. Your rancid father will try to twist your thoughts, as he did with all his children.
You twine your life around the people you love. And when they are gone, you grow around their absence instead. It is just another way they shape you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrug - she's accepted life and death, it is what it is

Text.Value: I think we have enough to be getting on with without the small-talk - don't you?

EditorData.NodeContext: Bare politeness - used when we ask her a personal question and she doesn't particularly want to answer (could range from actively disliking us to just putting us off)

Text.Value: Hah! No, no thank you - let the wiser members of my order wrinkle their brows over that particular phrase.

EditorData.NodeContext: Snort, absolutely not getting into the philosophical discussion - she just does the job

Text.Value: Some call the Harpers heroes. Others, petty meddlers who cannot help but stick their nose into every conflict they stumble across. The truth is in there somewhere.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sighing, shrugging. She's unfazed by the chatter - the Harpers can be (and often are) both things

Text.Value: Still - the Undercity shifts. We might search down there - or better yet, find a Bhaalist to lead us.
Then clean out your ears, and listen again.

EditorData.NodeContext: Flat, unimpressed

Text.Value: I fell in love with someone who was. And that is almost the same thing.

EditorData.NodeContext: Fond, remembering her husband Khalid (a topic she will not be drawn on here)

Text.Value: All I'm hearing is that he was a weakling.
I'm not certain you are older than me.
Bhaal frightens me.
We try to work towards a common balance. If every other faction finds us equally annoying, that is probably a sign that we are succeeding.

EditorData.NodeContext: Stating simply, laying down her less grand view of what they do

Text.Value: My mind is still my own. I plan to keep it that way.
And for a time, I did. But my comrades would use a rather irritating phrase: 'A Harper never leaves the chorus - she simply goes to spread the song.'

EditorData.NodeContext: Her annoying comrades

Text.Value: I am no expert on the matter, despite all my experience. But - if anything I know can help you to resist your father... only ask it.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim resolve. She'll do everything she can to help us, even if she isn't sure what exactly that is

Text.Value: Surely people understand that the Harpers are working for the greater good.
Want to tell me more about this someone you loved?
Who are you speaking to? Maybe I'm the parasite, puppeting this body.
If you are asking whether love and joy are beyond you, just because of the taint in your blood...

EditorData.NodeContext: Very nostalgic, former Jaheira romancers should feel a little heartbroken, but she shouldn't entirely imply it was her.

Text.Value: They showed me how to fight with sword as well as spell, and gave me ample causes to wield them for. If I was not always the truest believer in every cause, well...
You've never known a Bhaalspawn to go mad, have you?
Oh dear - should I brace myself for some fashion advice?

EditorData.NodeContext: Deadpan

Text.Value: So I returned to the fold. Returned to the city. Eventually, they hung a title around my neck: 'High Harper'. And I still do not know how to play one.

EditorData.NodeContext: Helpless shrug at her now grand title. She doesn't know how she wound up here, either.

Text.Value: What can you tell me about the Harpers?
I have never known a warrior who would go so far out of his way to avoid a fight. Which meant the few he chose were usually the right ones.

EditorData.NodeContext: General amused / fond rememberance

Text.Value: You speak of a battle more than a century past. Bhaal's minions led us through a maze in the Undercity, older than Baldur's Gate itself.
A Bhaalspawn can sire children, certainly. We have Sarevok and Orin as proof of that. Whether they should...
There are things in our nature we might unwittingly pass on, yes. But I do not believe them stronger than the things we choose to pass on.
Discuss something else.
I wonder if past experience has taught the great god to fear - that another of his children might turn against him.
But you're staring - which means the tadpole has finally eaten your brain, or I have been talking too much. Either way, time to move - no?

EditorData.NodeContext: Closing off the topic, catching herself talking a lot and impatient to get going again (but not harshly so)

Text.Value: He was a Harper. A better one than me, truth be told - any idiot can swing a sword. But to believe in the cause, with the whole of your heart? A much trickier thing.

EditorData.NodeContext: Her general tone when talking about Khalid is not grief-stricken, but fond rememberance. Even then, it's not overly emotional - she keeps those feelings and memories for herself, but has no problem picking at the wound - it's as healed as it's ever going to be.

Text.Value: About that amulet I found in your house.
You seem like an odd pairing.
Hmm. I've learned not to unpick the legends so many have woven around our name. Seeing the hope die in a romantic's eyes - it is only funny the first few dozen times.

EditorData.NodeContext: A little mock-wary about getting into the topic - people have a lot of opinions about the Harpers - but relenting, dryly amused

Text.Value: I need to know more about the Bhaalspawn. About myself.
A Bhaalspawn can sire children, certainly. Whether they should...
If you have questions, ask. Just don't expect my answers to rhyme.

EditorData.NodeContext: Relenting to answer questions, but not overly begrudging. We've earned this

Text.Value: Did your friend live happily, once Bhaal was dealt with?
But so long as you fear that power, there is hope. Fear means you are not fully mad - not yet.
Meaning that whatever cause I turned my hand to, there I would find them. Harpers, stuffed with their own virtue - but always there. Always trying to help.

EditorData.NodeContext: Wry

Text.Value: Mm? No, not really.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not fobbing us off, just amused - those are her memories, and she won't be drawn into waxing poetic (Right now). Think old man Steve Rogers when asked about Peggy at the end of Avengers: Endgame.

Text.Value: There: have I fulfilled my role as your wise and wizened elder?

EditorData.NodeContext: A little wry - aware she was waxing poetic about the past

Text.Value: Never mind.
He sounds like he had true strength.
Speak of something else.
Ha! Bhaal was but the beginning. Be warned - a godspawn draws trouble like iron to lodestone.
You're not that old - are you?
You seem reluctant to discuss the past.
Naturally. Irenicus, or 'The Exile', sought to extract divinity from Bhaalspawn blood. Needless to say, he failed in quite catastrophic fashion - hence the cautionary part of the tale.
Leave.
It's different this time. The elder brain is a slave itself.
Is it true that you've fought the Dead Three before?
Recall what you know of Khalid.
The harder you resist, the darker your dreams become. Our camp was often roused by screams in the night, back then.
More than I would like. In my youth, I was a brief - and very much unwilling - member of a colony's hivemind.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bad taste in her mouth

Text.Value: You mentioned you know something of illithids.
There will be crusaders who wish to rid the world of your taint, or jealous minds who believe themselves more deserving of the power in your blood.
But then - who am I speaking to? You have far more experience than I.
But stay this apocalypse and I'll let you read my journals. Promise.
We paid little mind to the path ahead, let alone to how we might return. Or that we would return at all.
The druid in me would like to say it was a thing of balance. The younger woman recalls rather more about a fine bottom, and the habit not to speak unless he had something to say.

EditorData.NodeContext: Half jokingly hinting at what first attracted her to Khalid, who on the surface is very different to her.

Text.Value: I will not mince words: if what you told me is true, you are already further under Bhaal's power than my old friend ever was.
Oh, you might say that. I left their service and swore never to return. Multiple times, if I recall.

EditorData.NodeContext: Affirming, amused at her own hot-headedness in youth. She lost faith with the Harpers more than once, but always comes back.

Text.Value: I'm sure Gale has heard the cautionary tale of the mad mage Jon Irenicus.
If I wanted to spare Geraldus the same headaches, well... you know now why I needed him to be sure this is the life he wants.
Did the Bhaalspawn have children? Did they inherit his taint?
Was your camp bothered time and time again by a grotesque Butler?
Bhaal had his minions, certainly. But none that watched over their wards so diligently.
I think you've told me enough.
Don't tell me which. Against all life experience, I will choose to assume the best.

EditorData.NodeContext: Jaheira has said she "wise and wizened", player has said she's only one of those things.

Text.Value: Which is to say - yes. I am that old.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not overly harsh, but a little sardonic:

Text.Value: We can speak of old battles later - our plate is piled high with catastrophes enough for the present, hm?

EditorData.NodeContext: Trying to steer our attention back to our own fight - out of pragmatism, but also because she doesn't want to discuss the topic of Bhaal with us.

Text.Value: Do not be moved to pity. It is a predator, pinned in a trap.

EditorData.NodeContext: All joking aside, a gentle warning

Text.Value: He died. Alone, in pain, and far too young - murdered by a mage who craved immortality. I'll not grant it by naming him in the same breath as my husband.

EditorData.NodeContext: Flat. No great amount of pathos, just stating facts. Hint of contempt for 'the mage' (Irenicus from BG2) in the last statement.

Text.Value: Most Harpers swagger and flash their feathers to catch your attention. Khalid was of a quieter sort.

EditorData.NodeContext: General amused / fond rememberance

Synopsis: Jaheira's default dialogue. Topics range from her past life to her current goals as they develop. Unless otherwise stated, her tone is confident and to the point. She's a seasoned adventurer with a sardonic sense of humour - and a little less cynical than she might present herself to be.
